st this, but if it is... then yay  <br>
<br>
Anyway, I've been working on a Star Wars fan fiction trilogy since 1997, and I'm on Episode III of it now. For five years, the series has been serialized in the newsletter of a Star Wars fan club called Star Wars Unlimited. Now it's kind of stalled out...<br>
<br>
In a previous episode seven Sith Lords were released from a holocron into new bodies. Four have been killed, including the most powerful who the others all feared enough to be subservient to him. Now, there are three left (all Masters), and, of course, there can be only two (one Master and an Apprentice). So, we have three Sith Lords battling each other and infiltrating the New Republic, each trying to create their own armies so that they can better challenge the other two. One Sith Lord has infiltrated the rebuilt Jedi Temple on Coruscant, another now commands the army of the previously dominant Sith Lord, and is searching for a new apprentice. The third, a Hutt, has infiltrated the government of the Bothan people and owns the Bothan governor (whom he put into power).<br>
<br>
In the beginning of the story, the Jedi Protector of Bothawui (the Bothan homeworld) disappears, attacked by Bothan soldiers. Now, three Jedi have come to investigate what happened. Already, they have discovered that the governor and his men were behind the Protector's disappearance, or at least are covering up for whoever kidnapped him. They know that a Sith Lord is on Bothawui, but they don't know if there's a connection between him and the governor, and they don't know where he is. One Jedi is staying at the Governor's Mansion, and the other two (both Padawan) are actively investigating the Protector's disappearance and are staying at the New Republic Embassy. <br>
<br>
Through the Ambassador, the Padawans have found out that many other people have vanished from Bothawui, but they don't know if there's a connection between them and the Governor and the Hutt. I need to find a good way for them to discover that the Governor and Hutt are working together, that the Governor's men are kidnapping people with high midichlorian counts so that the Hutt can create an army of force-using zombies to use in his war against the other two Sith Lords. <br>
<br>
I suck at writing mysteries like this, I really don't have any idea as to how to go about it. If you have any ideas, I would really love to hear them.  <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uformerlyknownassky.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Formerly Known As Sky</A> at: 9/25/02 8:35:52 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/upopularmisconception.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Popular Misconception</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/26/02 1:41:09 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm26.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=805.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Some advice</span><hr size=1> There are several ways that a mystery can be solved. <br>
<br>
1) The villain gives himself away due to the overwhelming pressure of conscious - The Telltale Heat.<br>
<br>
2) The hero pieces together using observations and clues that he finds - Agatha Christie style.<br>
<br>
3) The hero can stumble upon the solution out of blind luck - Inspector Gadget<br>
<br>
4) The hero can infiltrate the enemy forces - James Bond<br>
<br>
Standard to all mysterys is a crime, a villain, a detective and the clues. <br>
<br>
Probably the best way, is to visualise your crime and conspiracy before the jedi arrive, look at the links and then sever them to find out where the clues would be. <br>
<br>
Maybe the Hutt like a particular food and the governor has a lot in the kitchens. Maybe there is someone on the inside who wants out and sees the Jedi as a way out. Maybe the Governor has a lot of texts on the Hutt or perhaps there is a room the Jedi can sense that they cannot see a door too.  <br>
<br>
There are endless possibilities and some of the examples are off the top of my head. As long as it makes sense and you keep the reader guessing then you should be okay. <br>
